The Optimized Shard Structure (6 Primary Shards)
QRASL's architecture now features 6 primary, distinct shards, with the conceptual role of a seventh (formerly Shard 4) integrated into others to enhance efficiency and reduce complexity. Each shard is purpose-built:

Shards 0 & 1 (General Execution / High-Interaction DApps): These high-throughput shards utilize the Intent-Driven Hierarchical DAG Block (IHDB) protocol. They are ideal for complex dApps requiring numerous user interactions. Shard 0 might cater to dApps with broad state dependencies, while Shard 1 could be fine-tuned for applications with more localized, high-frequency state changes.

Shard 2 (Auxiliary Computation & ZKP Verification): Running a simpler Adaptive DAG Block structure (a streamlined version of IHDB, omitting solver networks and micro-rollups), this shard is dedicated to specialized tasks like verifiable off-chain computation results, oracle services, complex background calculations, and optimized ZKP verification for the network.

Shard 3 (High-Throughput DeFi / Complex Transactions): This shard leverages a specialized variant of the IHDB protocol, meticulously optimized for the demands of decentralized finance. It's engineered for high transaction speeds, low latency, intricate state interactions (e.g., multi-layered lending protocols, complex derivatives), and efficient processing of economic intents via DeFi-centric Solvers.

(Shard 4 - Integrated): The role of Shard 4 has been consolidated. Its potential use for experimental features or overflow is now part of Shard 5's customizable nature or managed by dynamic resource allocation.

Shard 5 (Application-Specific / Customizable): This shard provides unparalleled flexibility for deploying large-scale DApps or specialized subnetworks. It can be configured to run either IHDBs for complex applications or simpler block structures for more straightforward tasks, effectively absorbing the experimental capacity previously envisioned for a separate Shard 4.

Shard 6 (Governance & Data Bridge): Operating with a secure and auditable Simpler Adaptive DAG Block, this shard is the bedrock of QRASL's governance and data integrity. It executes on-chain governance decisions, hosts the proposal system, records state commitments from all other shards, anchors the DID system, and manages historical data. Its 30 Delegators and 30 Validators are chosen via staking and community endorsement, ensuring robust and decentralized oversight.
